> Why this fix
> 
> - Ensures HTTP headers remain ASCII-safe on the wire in compliance with Kestrelâ€™s validation and HTTP/1.x rules.
> - Localizes the change to StaticAssets where dev/runtime headers are appended from manifests, without relaxing Kestrel validation.
> - Maintains backward compatibility; only URL-bearing headers with non-ASCII segments are modified (by percent-encoding), which is the correct interoperable form.
> 
> Manual verification steps
> 
> - Create a Blazor Web App (WASM/Auto) project under a path with a non-ASCII name (e.g., é¡¹ç›®), target .NET 9/10.
> - Run in Development and request a page that includes static assets the dev/runtime stack touches.
> - Before: Kestrel throws Invalid non-ASCII in header (0x9879). After: Page loads and Link headers show percent-encoded URLs (e.g., /_content/%E9%A1%B9%E7%9B%AE/app.js).
> 
> Notes
> 
> - If additional URL-bearing headers are introduced in StaticAssets later, extend HeaderValueEncoder.Sanitize accordingly.
> - This change does not alter StaticFiles middleware behavior; it only affects StaticAssets dev/runtime behavior where arbitrary headers from manifests are appended verbatim today.

